Following independence, the government of [[Guinea]] adopted rules of transcription for the [[languages of Guinea]] based on the characters and diacritic combinations available on typewriters of that period.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} This alphabet was used officially until 1989.
==Guinea language orthography== The Guinea alphabet made use of several [[Digraph (orthography)|digraphs]] (including either "h" or "y" as the second letter), some of which represent consonants not present in European languages, and two [[diacritic]]s ([[grave accent]] and [[Diaeresis (diacritic)|diaeresis]]) for open vowels.
This system was widely used within the country but differed from the orthographies of neighboring countries of [[West Africa]], as developed in the wake of the 1966 Bamako expert meeting on harmonizing orthographies of the [[cross-border language]]s of the region.
In 1989, following a meeting on reform of the alphabet in 1988,<ref>Gilbert Sâa Ifono, "L'activité terminologique en Guinée," [http://www.termisti.org/rifal/PDF/tn09/tn09.pdf RINT 9, June 1993]</ref> it was decided to adopt an orthography similar to the [[African reference alphabet]] used elsewhere in the region.<ref>Diallo, Alpha Mamadou, ''Usages et images des langues en guinée'', Université de Conakry. [http://www.unice.fr/ILF-CNRS/ofcaf/19/DIALLO.pdf]</ref><ref>Diallo, Amadou; ''Étude sur le rôle de l'éducation non formelle dans la stratégie de réduction de la pauvreté (SRP) en Guinée'', Ministère du Plan de la République de Guinée/ GTZ, Conakry 3/2006. [http://www.srp-guinee.org/download/diallo-education-non-formelle-et-srp.pdf]</ref><ref>Effectuated by decree 019/PRG/SGG/89</ref>
A summary table of the digraphs and diacritics of the old alphabet, and their extended Latin equivalents in the new system, follows: :{| class="wikitable sortable" ! Pre-1989 ! Post-1989 ! Language(s) ! IPA value |- | [[Bh (digraph)|bh]] | [[ɓ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]] | {{IPA|ɓ}} |- | [[Dh (digraph)|dh]] | [[ɗ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]] | {{IPA|ɗ}} |- | [[Gh (digraph)|gh]] | [[ɠ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]] | {{IPA|ɠ}} |- | [[Kh (digraph)|kh]] | [[x]] | [[Susu language|Susu]] | {{IPA|ɣ}} |- | [[Nh (digraph)|nh]] | [[ŋ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]], [[Maninka language|Maninka]] | {{IPA|ŋ}} |- | [[Ny (digraph)|ny]] | [[ɲ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]], [[Maninka language|Maninka]], [[Susu language|Susu]] | {{IPA|ɲ}} |- | [[Yh (digraph)|yh]] | [[ƴ]] | [[Pular language|Pular]] | {{IPA|/ʔʲ/}} |- | [[è]] | [[ɛ]] | [[Maninka language|Maninka]], [[Susu language|Susu]] | {{IPA|ɛ}} |- | [[ö]] | [[ɔ]] | [[Maninka language|Maninka]], [[Susu language|Susu]] | {{IPA|ɔ}} |- | [[Dy (digraph)|dy]] | [[j]] | [[Pular language|Pular]], [[Maninka language|Maninka]] | {{IPA|dʒ}} |- | [[Ty (digraph)|ty]] | [[c]] | [[Pular language|Pular]], [[Maninka language|Maninka]] | {{IPA|tʃ}} |}
