'''Indulis''' is a [[Latvian masculine given name]], borne by more than 1,000 men in [[Latvia]].<ref>PMLP database</ref> Its nameday is celebrated on 2 January.

The name has two possible derivations, one from a Baltic word meaning "gift", and the other as a diminutive of Indriķis, the Latvian form of [[Heinrich (given name)|Heinrich]].

Indulis was the name of the hero of the legend of Indulis and Ārija, the Latvian [[Romeo and Juliet]], set in the 13th century during the [[Germany|German]] conquest, which relates the tragic love of Indulis, a [[Curonians|Curonian]] chieftain, and Ārija, daughter of a German military commander. The name was revived, along with many other medieval names, in the late 19th century, and was brought to especial prominence by the poet and dramatist [[Rainis]] with the publication in 1911 of his play ''"Indulis un Ārija"''.

As a modern name, Indulis is better-known than many Latvian names because of [[Indulis Emsis]], Prime Minister of Latvia in 2004, the first [[Latvian Green Party|Green]] head of state in the world.

==Notable people with the name Indulis==
*[[Indulis Bekmanis]] (born 1989), Latvian professional road cyclist
*[[Indulis Emsis]] (born 1952), Latvian biologist and politician

